<header class="header">
  <h1>Smart Soil Sensor vs Manual Moisture Meter for Gardens</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    One gives you data anywhere — the other gives you certainty on the spot.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Smart soil sensors are best for remote monitoring, while manual moisture meters are better for quick, reliable in-person checks.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Both tools measure soil moisture, but they solve very different problems. Choosing between them depends less on accuracy and more on how and when you need the information.
  </p>
  <p>
    Most gardeners don’t need both — but many benefit from using each in the right role.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: Which Should You Use?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best for remote monitoring:</strong> smart sensor.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for quick checks:</strong> manual meter.</li>
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> depends on whether you need remote access.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The difference is access, not just measurement.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Each Tool Works</h2>

  <h3>Smart Soil Sensors</h3>
  <p>
    Measure moisture electronically and transmit data to an app or system. They can provide continuous readings over time.
  </p>

  <h3>Manual Moisture Meters</h3>
  <p>
    Use probes inserted into the soil to give an immediate reading when checked in person.
  </p>

  <p>
    One is continuous and remote. The other is immediate and local.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Accuracy vs Reliability</h2>

  <p>
    Both tools can provide useful data, but consistency matters more than precision.
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>smart sensors show trends over time</li>
    <li>manual meters provide instant snapshots</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The best tool is the one you trust and understand.
  </p>
</section>

